name: URChildren
str: Children born to those assigned female at birth
help:
JSON format help for AgeAvg (age vs. average) plots
----------------------------------------------------
Downloadable JSON files for Who Are We Now? are dictionaries.

They always have a "type" field specifying the plot type, and a "name"
field, specifying the plot name. https://whoarewenow.net/plotname
will redirect you to the location of any plot in its chapter.

This one's type is "AgeAvg", for plotting weighted averages, quantiles,
and medians as a function of the respondent's age.

The data are specified in such a way that dynamic rebinning by age is
supported, as well as either weighted or unweighted plotting or analysis.
The weights are calculated using stratified sampling based on demographic
criteria, as explained in the appendix https://whoarewenow.net/appendix.

JSON entries with example values:

Key        Value                 Comment
--------   --------------------  ---------------------------------
"type"   : "AgeAvg"
"name"   : "PlotName"
"val"    : "Number of children"  Name of the dependent variable
"x"      : [18,93]               Minimum and maximum+1 age
"bins"   : [18,25,30,40,60,80]   Age bin boundaries
"z"      : [0.68, 0.95, 0.997]   Quantiles (see Appendix)
"seq"    : [Seq1,Seq2,...]       Each sequence is a map per below
"series" : [Series1,Series2,...] Each series is a map per below

Seq specifies the sequence of "stops" in the visualization:

Key        Value                 Comment
--------   --------------------  -------------------------------------------
"i"      : [{0:[0,1,2]},1:[0]}]  Indices of series and quantiles to render
"y"      : [0,3.5]               Value range for this stop

Series specifies the data for all series, as specified by each "i" in "seq":

Key        Value                 Comment
--------   --------------------  -------------------------------------------
"s"      : "All respondents"     Series label
"c"      : "black"               Series color
"v"      : SeriesData            Series data, described below
"r"      : NoiseData             Precalculated random noise, described below

SeriesData consists of nested dictionaries as follows:
{ weight : { value : { age : count } } }
where weight and value are floating point, and age and count are integers.
This format is relatively compact (in effect, a sparse matrix) due to the
fact that the quantities treated involve repeating weights (due to stratified
sampling with a limited number of strata), repeating values, and repeating
ages.

NoiseData is similarly:
{ weight : { value : { age : [values] } } }
where [values] is a list of uniformly random zeroes and ones. These are used
for "fuzzing" small integer values (such as number of children) to produce
more informative plots, as described in the appendix. Random values are
precalculated to make the plots in the book deterministic, but of course
should be ignored in any re-analysis.

Some dictionary key/value pairs are unimportant, used only for debugging or
visualization, and are not documented above.

For more information on the project see https://whoarewenow.net#about
